¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨norm‚ù≠ is a real-valued functional that is ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (a) non-negative, ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (b) definite, ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (c) absolutely homogeneous, ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ (d) and satisifies a triangle inequality. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The triangle inequality property requires that the norm
    applied to the sum of any two vectors is less than the sum
    of the norms on those vectors. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨normed space‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨norm space‚ù≠) is an ordered pair: a
    vector space whose field is the real or complex numbers and
    a norm on the space. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We require the vector space to be over the field of real
    or complex numbers because of absolute homogeneity: the
    absolute value of a scalar must be defined. ‚¶â
‚¶â

